To create a simple search bar using PHP, we will use HTML for the layout and CSS for styling (optional). For searching functionality, we'll use PHP to query a database. Here's a basic example that demonstrates how you can implement a search feature.

This example assumes you have a MySQL database set up with a table named `items` containing columns for `id`, `name`, and `description`. The code will retrieve data from this table based on the search query entered in the form.

### Step 1: HTML Form

First, create an HTML form to input the search query. We'll add some basic CSS for styling.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Search Bar</title>
    <style>
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; }
        #searchForm {
            width: 50%;
            margin: 40px auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>
<div id="searchForm">
    <form action="" method="post" autocomplete="off">
        <input type="text" name="query" placeholder="Search here...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <?php 
    // If a search query has been submitted
    if (isset($_POST['query'])) {
        $searchQuery = $_POST['query'];

        // SQL Query to get results from the database based on the search query
        $sql = "SELECT * FROM items WHERE name LIKE '%$searchQuery%' OR description LIKE '%$searchQuery%'";

        // Assume you're using a MySQL connection
        require_once 'connect.php';
        $result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);

        if (mysqli_num_rows($result) > 0) {
            ?>
            <h2>Search Results</h2>
            <table border="1" cellpadding="10" cellspacing="0">
                <tr>
                    <th>ID</th>
                    <th>Name</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>

                <?php
                // Loop through the results and display them in a table
                while($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result)) {
                    echo '<tr>';
                    echo '<td>' . $row['id'] . '</td>';
                    echo '<td>' . $row['name'] . '</td>';
                    echo '<td>' . $row['description'] . '</td>';
                    echo '</tr>';
                }
                ?>
            </table>

            <?php
        } else {
            // Display a message if no results are found
            echo "<h2>No results found.</h2>";
        }

        // Close the connection
        mysqli_close($conn);
    }
    ?>
</div>

</body>
</html>
```

### Step 2: Database Connection (in `connect.php`)

Create a file named `connect.php` in the same directory as your search bar script to include the database connection details.

```php
<?php
// For MySQL connections, you might need to adjust this based on your server setup.
$servername = "localhost";
$username = "your_username";
$password = "your_password";
$dbname = "your_database_name";

$conn = new mysqli($servername, $username, $password, $dbname);

if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
}
?>
```

This example is very basic and you should consider security measures to prevent SQL injection (e.g., using prepared statements). Always remember that displaying results directly from a database can be vulnerable, especially if the data contains user input.

